South African Stocks Climb For a Third Day; Mondi Advances, Platmin Falls

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-05T16:05:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-05/south-african-stocks-climb-for-a-third-day-evraz-highveld-mondi-advance.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index increased to the highest level since Feb. 21,
gaining 193.09, or 0.6 percent, to 32,630.86 at the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, jumped to the highest in a month, climbing 2.35 rand,
or 0.9 percent, to 276.25 rand. Copper snapped two days of
losses as Chinese manufacturing expanded for the first time in
four months in March.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest producer
of the metal, added 2.54 rand, or 0.8 percent, to 331.24 rand,
extending its gain this year to 1.3 percent. Gold futures jumped
to a record in  New York  as sovereign-debt concerns boosted
demand for the precious metal as an alternative asset.  Gold
Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-biggest gold producer,
advanced for a sixth day, climbing 1.50 rand, or 1.3 percent, to
120.75 rand, the highest in almost a month.  Mondi Plc (MND SJ),  Europe ’s largest maker of office paper,
snapped two days of losses, rising 28 cents, or 0.4 percent, to
65.35 rand. Deutsche Bank AG restarted coverage of the stock
with a “buy” rating.  Platmin Ltd. (PLN)  , a platinum mining company, lost 10
cents, or 1.7 percent, to 5.80 rand, the lowest in almost a
week. Platmin said Craig Shaw has been appointed as its new
chief financial officer.  Raubex Ltd. (RBX SJ), a South African road builder, fell
the most this month, dropping 51 cents, or 2.6 percent, to 18.84
rand. Earnings will decline by as much as 30 percent in the year
through February, compared to the year earlier, said Raubex in a
statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
